w popular and medical understandings of the mind and body were reframed by the social, cultural and political structures of 'modern life'. Essays within the collection examine ways in which cancer, suicide, and social degeneration were seen as products of the stresses and strains of 'new' ways of living. Others explore the legal, institutional, and intellectual changes that contributed to modern medical practice. The volume traces ways that physiological and psychological problems were being constituted in relation to each other, and to their social contexts, and offers new ways of contextualising the problems of modernity facing us in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistory (General). 0aMedicine (General). 0aModern history, 1453-. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aGood health and well-being.1 aArnold-Forster, Agnes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlayney, Steffan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickson, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickson, Melissa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHamlin, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMathias, Manon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMukharji, Projit Bihari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMyllykangas, Mikko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRiotte, Torsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchlicht, Laurens, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShutt